You will have a hard time convicing me that any tex-mex restaurant in the valley is as good as some of our best authentic mexican cuisine, so Chevy's starts a leg down in my estimation.
It's not bad, and the homemade tortillas are actually somewhat impressive.
Still, I would advise exhausting all other mexican options first, then, in the tex-mex pecking order, going to Ajo Al's, or if that doesn't work, try Chevy's.
It is a good place to take a large group and drink margaritas and celebrate and non-romantic event, such as a birthday or graduation.
Celebrants are given a large sombrero, which, invariably, they will wear for the duration of the night out after sipping on a little too much tequila.
Don't believe me?
You'll see.

Summertime happy hour weeknights until 7:00PM- beer and margaritas under $3.00.

Chevy's five years ago was crisp and fresh and the salsa was great.
The tortillas were hot and fresh and the staff engaging.
It was a lovely place to have fun.
Then it took a nose dive in every single area and it didn't seem to care.
Quality and service and food, man we had some nasty times and stopped visiting.
We thought fresh my ***.
If you had made a suggestion of going to Chevy's I would roll my eyes.
Thanks but no thanks.
On a lark, maybe desperation, we went back this weekend.
They have updated the menu, the staff, the service and the place is back functioning again.
I asked management what happened and they divulged the handling of parent company Pepsi was a disaster for the Chevy's branding and they have been sold to new people.
It shows.
If you used to enjoy Chevy's and then over the past few years stopped, then it's time to go back.
The fire shrimp is back, the service is back, the machino is working and things remind me of when I first tried them out.
We were full, and satisfied.
If you have any issues with your new experience they are listening now.
Welcome Back Chevy's.

I think Chevy's saving grace is their happy hour.
Because honestly, there is no other reason I'd come here.
I've been several times over the years and the food has always been meh.
With the abundance of Mexican food in Phoenix, there are so many other places to get good food at prices that are cheaper making Chevy's a last place loser on my list.
Last night we ordered the flautas and the nachos off the happy hour menu.
The flautas were oddly salty.
I couldn't figure out if it was the sauce they had put on top or the actual flauta.
The nachos were pretty standard.
Loaded with beans and some meat (I think it was chicken).
Paired with their house margaritas, they weren't bad.
The margaritas were okay.
Nothing amazing, but standard.
I did notice they have a $30 and a $41 margarita on their menu.
If I was going to drink like that, I think I'd want better accompaniments.
The service is okay.
At happy hour our server was friendly and quick but I've gone and had people who just disappear or do the minimum amount of work.
Like I said, their happy hour is their saving grace.
For $3 you can order a few select appetizers (flautas, nachos, fajita nachos are among some of the items).
Well drinks, draft beer (Bud and Bud Light), wine, and house margaritas are $3.
For $0.25 more, you can get a fruit margarita.
While at happy hour there were several people there that were from out of town.
I felt like I needed to be a good citizen and tell them that there so many other places they could have gone.
But I didn't.
They'll just have to use Yelp themselves.

